{
  "texts": [
    "METHODOLOGY A.",
    "Problem FormulationWe formulate the ANA task as a multi-instance multi-label (MIML) learning problem, and an overview of the proposed framework is shown in Fig. 2.",
    "Given a set of unaltered microscope ANA images and their ground truth labels {(x i, y i)} n i=1, the goal is to learn a function that takes an image x i as input and predicts ŷi to best match y i.",
    "Let L = {l 1, l 2,..., l K } be the set of predefined ANA pattern labels (e.g., Golgi, Nucleolar), where each l k denotes a specific pattern.To address the complexity of image-level prediction in ANA classification, we adopt a divide-and-aggregate strategy.",
    "Specifically, each ANA image is decomposed into a bag of instances, denoted asx i = {x 1 i, x 2 i,..., x Ni i },where N i is the number of extracted instances from image x i."
  ]
}